  "prompt": "What is the difference between CNY and CNH currencies?",
  "response": "CNY and CNH are two different representations of the Chinese Yuan (Renminbi):\n\nCNY (Onshore Renminbi):\n- Traded within mainland China\n- Strictly controlled by the People's Bank of China\n- Subject to more government restrictions\n- Used for domestic transactions\n- Exchanged at official rates set by the Chinese government\n\nCNH (Offshore Renminbi):\n- Traded outside mainland China, primarily in Hong Kong\n- Less regulated and more market-driven\n- More flexible exchange rates\n- Used for international transactions\n- Allows for easier cross-border trading and investment\n- Can fluctuate more freely compared to CNY\n\nKey differences:\n1. Location of trading\n2. Level of regulatory control\n3. Exchange rate flexibility\n4. Purpose of use\n\nThe existence of two versions allows China to manage its currency more strategically in international markets while maintaining control over domestic financial systems.",
